==fff==
{{Short description|Japanese purification rite and festival}}
{{Expand Japanese|大祓|date=November 2023}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2023}}
{{Japanese Imperial Rituals}}
'''Ōharae-shiki''' is a [[Shinto]] ritual also known as the Great Purification.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.senninso.com/oharae-thegreatpurification/ | title=OHARAE 大祓: "The Great Purification" | date=January 2023 }}</ref><ref name="Namiki">{{Cite web |last=Namiki |first=Kazuko |title=Ōharae |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9119 |access-date=9 November 2023 |website=[[Kokugakuin University]] Encyclopedia of Shinto}}</ref> The name Oharae literally means Great [[Harae]].<ref name="Namiki" />

The ritual was held biannually as a festival at the end of the sixth and twelfth months, but also on an ad hoc basis whenever a great purification was needed, such as after someone committed an offense, or a [[Daijosai]] or an unmarried prince or princess visited [[Ise Jingu]] or the [[Kamo Shrine|Kamo Shrines]].<ref name="Namiki" /><ref name="Hardacre-2016" />{{rp|7}}

It is hosted annually on June 30<ref>{{Cite web |title=Nagoshi no Oharae Purification Ritual |url=https://www.kamigamojinja.jp/en/rituals/nagoshi-no-oharae-purification-ritual/ |access-date=2023-06-05 |website=Kamo Wakeikazuchi Jinja Shrine (Kamigamo Jinja) |language=ja}}</ref> and on December 30.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Meador |first=Spencer |date=2017-07-04 |title=Oharae |url=http://sanpai-japan.com/2017/07/04/oharae/ |access-date=2023-06-05 |website=Sanpai Japan |language=en-US}}</ref> The latter is sometimes held on New Year's Eve.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Shiwasu Oharae-shiki (Great Purification Ceremony in December) {{!}} Samukawa-jinja Shrine |url=https://samukawajinjya.jp/en/festival/shiwasuoharae.html |access-date=2023-06-05 |website=Samukawa-jinja Shrine Official Website |language=en}}</ref>

The Engishiki specified imperial involvement with four festivals, the [[Kinen-sai]], the two Ōharae-shiki and [[Niiname-no-Matsuri]] for tribute.<ref name="Hardacre-2016">{{Cite book |last=Hardacre |first=Helen |title=Shinto: A History |date=2016-11-11 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-062171-1 |edition=Illustrated |location=New York (N.Y.) |language=English}}</ref>{{rp|36}}

[[Oharae no Kotoba]] are prayers used in this process.<ref>[https://www.ookunitamajinja.or.jp/pdf/202012_OHARAE_3.pdf The Great Purification chant] ookunitamajinja.or.jp</ref>

It is also done at [[Isonokami Shrine]]

== History ==
Historians state that regular Ōharae rites started at the end of the [[7th century|seventh century]]. They evolved over time, especially through the [[15th century|fifteenth century]]. These changes were linked to updates in the [[Ritsuryō|ritsuryō system]], a set of laws and rules, in the eighth century.<ref name="Namiki" />

In the [[Edo period]] (1603–1868), Ōharae changed again. In the [[Meiji era|Meiji period]] (1868–1912), some parts of the old rite were reestablished.<ref name="Namiki" />

Purification became more important to prepare for this ritual and {{ill|Yoori|ja|節折}} became more prominent in the Meiji restoration.<ref name="Hardacre-2016" />{{rp|362}}

== Minazuki-barae ==
People often mix up the Ōharae in the sixth month with Minazuki-barae (水無月祓), another purification rite that takes place at that time. However, each had its own purpose and importance in court rituals.<ref name="Namiki" />

==See also==
* [[Garland]]

